# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clock-domain-crossing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Asynchronous circuits are contrasted with synchronous circuits, in which changes to the signal values in the circuit are triggered by repetitive pulses called a clock signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Most digital devices today use synchronous circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] However asynchronous circuits have a potential to be much faster, have a lower level of power consumption, electromagnetic interference, and better modularity in large systems.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Asynchronous circuits are an active area of research in digital logic design.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] It was not until the 1990s when viability of the asynchronous circuits was shown by real-life commercial products.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] All digital logic circuits can be divided into combinational logic, in which the output signals depend only on the current input signals, and sequential logic, in which the output depends both on current input and on past inputs.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In other words, sequential logic is combinational logic with memory.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Virtually all practical digital devices require sequential logic.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Sequential logic can be divided into two types, synchronous logic and asynchronous logic.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In synchronous logic circuits, an electronic oscillator generates a repetitive series of equally spaced pulses called the *clock signal*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The clock signal is supplied to all the components of the IC.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Flip-flops only flip when triggered by the edge of the clock pulse, so changes to the logic signals throughout the circuit begin at the same time and at regular intervals.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The output of all memory elements in a circuit is called the *state* of the circuit.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The state of a synchronous circuit changes only on the clock pulse.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The changes in signal require a certain amount of time to propagate through the combinational logic gates of the circuit.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This time is called a propagation delay.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] As of 2021, timing of modern synchronous ICs takes significant engineering efforts and sophisticated design automation tools.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Designers have to ensure that clock arrival is not faulty.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] With the ever-growing size and complexity of ICs (e.g.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In huge circuits, signals sent over clock distribution network often end up at different times at different parts.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This problem is widely known as "clock skew".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The maximum possible clock rate is capped by the logic path with the longest propagation delay, called the critical path.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Because of that, the paths that may operate quickly are idle most of the time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] A widely distributed clock network dissipates a lot of useful power and must run whether the circuit is receiving inputs or not.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Because of this level of complexity, testing and debugging takes over half of development time in all dimensions for synchronous circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The asynchronous circuits do not need a global clock, and the state of the circuit changes as soon as the inputs change.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The local functional blocks may be still employed but the *clock skew* problem still can be tolerated.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Since asynchronous circuits do not have to wait for a clock pulse to begin processing inputs, they can operate faster.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Their speed is theoretically limited only by the propagation delays of the logic gates and other elements.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] However, asynchronous circuits are more difficult to design and subject to problems not found in synchronous circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This is because the resulting state of an asynchronous circuit can be sensitive to the relative arrival times of inputs at gates.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] If transitions on two inputs arrive at almost the same time, the circuit can go into the wrong state depending on slight differences in the propagation delays of the gates.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In synchronous circuits this problem is less severe because race conditions can only occur due to inputs from outside the synchronous system, called *asynchronous inputs*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Although some fully asynchronous digital systems have been built (see below), today asynchronous circuits are typically used in a few critical parts of otherwise synchronous systems where speed is at a premium, such as signal processing circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The original theory of asynchronous circuits was created by David E.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This theory was presented later in the well-known book "Switching Theory" by Raymond Miller.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The term "asynchronous logic" is used to describe a variety of design styles, which use different assumptions about circuit properties.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] These vary from the bundled delay model – which uses "conventional" data processing elements with completion indicated by a locally generated delay model – to delay-insensitive design – where arbitrary delays through circuit elements can be accommodated.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The latter style tends to yield circuits which are larger than bundled data implementations, but which are insensitive to layout and parametric variations and are thus "correct by design".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Asynchronous logic is the logic required for the design of asynchronous digital systems.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] These function without a clock signal and so individual logic elements cannot be relied upon to have a discrete true/false state at any given time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Boolean (two valued) logic is inadequate for this and so extensions are required.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Vasyukevich developed an approach based upon new logical operations which he called *venjunction* (with asynchronous operator "*x*∠*y*" standing for "switching *x* on the background *y*" or "if *x* when *y* then") and *sequention* (with priority signs "*x**i*≻*x**j*" and "*x**i*≺*x**j*").
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This takes into account not only the current value of an element, but also its history.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Fant developed a different theoretical treatment of asynchronous logic in his work *Logically determined design* in 2005 which used four-valued logic with *null* and *intermediate* being the additional values.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This architecture is important because it is quasi-delay-insensitive.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Smith and Jia Di developed an ultra-low-power variation of Fant's Null Convention Logic that incorporates multi-threshold CMOS.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This variation is termed Multi-threshold Null Convention Logic (MTNCL), or alternatively Sleep Convention Logic (SCL).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Petri nets are an attractive and powerful model for reasoning about asynchronous circuits (see Subsequent models of concurrency).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] A particularly useful type of interpreted Petri nets, called Signal Transition Graphs (STGs), was proposed independently in 1985 by Leonid Rosenblum and Alex Yakovlev and Tam-Anh Chu.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Since then, STGs have been studied extensively in theory and practice, which has led to the development of popular software tools for analysis and synthesis of asynchronous control circuits, such as Petrify and Workcraft.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Subsequent to Petri nets other models of concurrency have been developed that can model asynchronous circuits including the Actor model and process calculi.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] A variety of advantages have been demonstrated by asynchronous circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] There are several ways to create asynchronous communication channels that can be classified by their protocol and data encoding.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Despite involving more transitions per communication, circuits implementing four-phase protocols are usually faster and simpler than two-phase protocols because the signal lines return to their original state by the end of each communication.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In two-phase protocols, the circuit implementations would have to store the state of the signal line internally.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Note that these basic distinctions do not account for the wide variety of protocols.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] These protocols may encode only requests and acknowledgements or also encode the data, which leads to the popular multi-wire data encoding.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Many other, less common protocols have been proposed including using a single wire for request and acknowledgment, using several significant voltages, using only pulses or balancing timings in order to remove the latches.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Another common way to encode the data is to use multiple wires to encode a single digit: the value is determined by the wire on which the event occurs.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This avoids some of the delay assumptions necessary with bundled-data encoding, since the request and the data are not separated anymore.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Bundled-data encoding uses one wire per bit of data with a request and an acknowledge signal; this is the same encoding used in synchronous circuits without the restriction that transitions occur on a clock edge.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The request and the acknowledge are sent on separate wires with one of the above protocols.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] These circuits usually assume a bounded delay model with the completion signals delayed long enough for the calculations to take place.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In operation, the sender signals the availability and validity of data with a request.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The receiver then indicates completion with an acknowledgement, indicating that it is able to process new requests.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] That is, the request is bundled with the data, hence the name "bundled-data".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Bundled-data circuits are often referred to as micropipelines, whether they use a two-phase or four-phase protocol, even if the term was initially introduced for two-phase bundled-data.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Multi-rail encoding uses multiple wires without a one-to-one relationship between bits and wires and a separate acknowledge signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Data availability is indicated by the transitions themselves on one or more of the data wires (depending on the type of multi-rail encoding) instead of with a request signal as in the bundled-data encoding.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This provides the advantage that the data communication is delay-insensitive.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Two common multi-rail encodings are one-hot and dual rail.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The one-hot (also known as 1-of-n) encoding represents a number in base n with a communication on one of the n wires.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The dual-rail encoding uses pairs of wires to represent each bit of the data, hence the name "dual-rail"; one wire in the pair represents the bit value of 0 and the other represents the bit value of 1.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] For example, a dual-rail encoded two bit number will be represented with two pairs of wires for four wires in total.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] During a data communication, communications occur on one of each pair of wires to indicate the data's bits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In the general case, an m $\times$ n encoding represent data as m words of base n.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Dual-rail encoding with a four-phase protocol is the most common and is also called *three-state encoding*, since it has two valid states (10 and 01, after a transition) and a reset state (00).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Another common encoding, which leads to a simpler implementation than one-hot, two-phase dual-rail is *four-state encoding*, or level-encoded dual-rail, and uses a data bit and a parity bit to achieve a two-phase protocol.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Asynchronous CPUs are one of several ideas for radically changing CPU design.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Unlike a conventional processor, a clockless processor (asynchronous CPU) has no central clock to coordinate the progress of data through the pipeline.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Instead, stages of the CPU are coordinated using logic devices called "pipeline controls" or "FIFO sequencers".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Basically, the pipeline controller clocks the next stage of logic when the existing stage is complete.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In this way, a central clock is unnecessary.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The biggest disadvantage of the clockless CPU is that most CPU design tools assume a clocked CPU (i.e., a synchronous circuit).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Many tools "enforce synchronous design practices".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Making a clockless CPU (designing an asynchronous circuit) involves modifying the design tools to handle clockless logic and doing extra testing to ensure the design avoids metastable problems.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The group that designed the AMULET, for example, developed a tool called LARD to cope with the complex design of AMULET3.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Despite all the difficulties numerous asynchronous CPUs have been built.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The ORDVAC of 1951 was a successor to the ENIAC and the first asynchronous computer ever built.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The ILLIAC II was the first completely asynchronous, speed independent processor design ever built; it was the most powerful computer at the time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] DEC PDP-16 Register Transfer Modules (ca.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] 1973) allowed the experimenter to construct asynchronous, 16-bit processing elements.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Delays for each module were fixed and based on the module's worst-case timing.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Since the mid-1980s, Caltech has designed four non-commercial CPUs in attempt to evaluate performance and energy efficiency of the asynchronous circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In 1988 the Caltech Asynchronous Microprocessor (CAM) was the first asynchronous, quasi delay-insensitive (QDI) microprocessor made by Caltech.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The processor had 16-bit wide RISC ISA and separate instruction and data memories.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] It was manufactured by MOSIS and funded by DARPA.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The project was supervised by the Office of Naval Research, the Army Research Office, and the Air Force Office of Scientific Research.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] During demonstrations, the researchers loaded a simple program which ran in a tight loop, pulsing one of the output lines after each instruction.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] This output line was connected to an oscilloscope.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] When a cup of hot coffee was placed on the chip, the pulse rate (the effective "clock rate") naturally slowed down to adapt to the worsening performance of the heated transistors.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] When liquid nitrogen was poured on the chip, the instruction rate shot up with no additional intervention.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Additionally, at lower temperatures, the voltage supplied to the chip could be safely increased, which also improved the instruction rate – again, with no additional configuration.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] When implemented in gallium arsenide (HGaAs 3) it was claimed to achieve 100MIPS.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Overall, the research paper interpreted the resultant performance of CAM as superior compared to commercial alternatives available at the time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In 1998 the MiniMIPS, an experimental, asynchronous MIPS I-based microcontroller was made.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Even though its SPICE-predicted performance was around 280 MIPS at 3.3 V the implementation suffered from several mistakes in layout (human mistake) and the results turned out be lower by about 40% (see table).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Made in 2003, it was a quasi delay-insensitive asynchronous microcontroller designed for energy efficiency.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The microcontroller's implementation followed the Harvard architecture.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In 2004, Epson manufactured the world's first bendable microprocessor called ACT11, an 8-bit asynchronous chip.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] Synchronous flexible processors are slower, since bending the material on which a chip is fabricated causes wild and unpredictable variations in the delays of various transistors, for which worst-case scenarios must be assumed everywhere and everything must be clocked at worst-case speed.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] The processor is intended for use in smart cards, whose chips are currently limited in size to those small enough that they can remain perfectly rigid.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] In 2014, IBM announced a SyNAPSE-developed chip that runs in an asynchronous manner, with one of the highest transistor counts of any chip ever produced.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/asynchronous-circuit] IBM's chip consumes orders of magnitude less power than traditional computing systems on pattern recognition benchmarks.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] In digital electronic design a **clock domain crossing** (CDC), or simply clock crossing, is the traversal of a signal in a synchronous digital circuit from one clock domain into another.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] If a signal does not assert long enough and is not registered, it may appear asynchronous on the incoming clock boundary.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] A synchronous system is composed of a single electronic oscillator that generates a clock signal, and its clock domain—the memory elements directly clocked by that signal from that oscillator, and the combinational logic attached to the outputs of those memory elements.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] Because of speed-of-light delays, timing skew, etc., the size of a clock domain in such a synchronous system is inversely proportional to the frequency of the clock.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] In early computers, typically all the digital logic ran in a single clock domain.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] At first, each CPU chip ran in its own single clock domain, and the rest of the digital logic of the computer ran in another slower clock domain.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] A few modern CPUs have such a high speed clock, that designers are forced to create several different clock domains on a single CPU chip.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] Different clock domains have clocks which have a different frequency, a different phase (due to either differing clock latency or a different clock source), or both.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] Either way the relationship between the clock edges in the two domains cannot be relied upon.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] Synchronizing a single bit signal to a clock domain with a higher frequency can be accomplished by registering the signal through a flip-flop that is clocked by the source domain, thus holding the signal long enough to be detected by the higher frequency clocked destination domain.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] CDC metastability issues can occur between asynchronous clock domains; this is in contrast to reset domain crossing metastability, which can occur between synchronous & asynchronous clock domains.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] To avoid issues with CDC metastability in the destination clock domain, a minimum of 2 stages of re-synchronization flip-flops are included in the destination domain.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] Synchronizing a single bit signal traversing into clock domain with a slower frequency is more cumbersome.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] This typically requires a register in each clock domain with a form of feedback from the destination domain to the source domain, indicating that the signal was detected.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] Other potential clock domain crossing design errors include glitches and data loss.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/clock-domain-crossing] In some cases, clock gating can result in two clock domains where the "slower" domain changes from one second to the next.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In electronics, **flip-flops** and **latches** are circuits that have two stable states that can store state information – a bistable multivibrator.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit can be made to change state by signals applied to one or more control inputs and will output its state (often along with its logical complement).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It is the basic storage element in sequential logic.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches are fundamental building blocks of digital electronics systems used in computers, communications, and many other types of systems.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches are used as data storage elements to store a single *bit* (binary digit) of data; one of its two states represents a *one* and the other represents a *zero*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Such data storage can be used for storage of *state*, and such a circuit is described as sequential logic in electronics.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When used in a finite-state machine, the output and next state depend not only on its current input, but also on its current state (and hence, previous inputs).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It can also be used for counting of pulses, and for synchronizing variably-timed input signals to some reference timing signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The term flip-flop has historically referred generically to both level-triggered (asynchronous, transparent, or opaque) and edge-triggered (synchronous, or clocked) circuits that store a single bit of data using gates.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Modern authors reserve the term *flip-flop* exclusively for edge-triggered storage elements and *latches* for level-triggered ones.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The terms *edge-triggered*, and *level-triggered* may be used to avoid ambiguity.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When a level-triggered latch is enabled, it becomes transparent, but an edge-triggered flip-flop's output only changes on a clock edge (either positive going or negative going).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Different types of flip-flops and latches are available as integrated circuits, usually with multiple elements per chip.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] For example, 74HC75 is a quadruple transparent latch in the 7400 series.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The first electronic latch was invented in 1918 by the British physicists William Eccles and F.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It was initially called the *Eccles–Jordan trigger circuit* and consisted of two active elements (vacuum tubes).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The design was used in the 1943 British Colossus codebreaking computer and such circuits and their transistorized versions were common in computers even after the introduction of integrated circuits, though latches and flip-flops made from logic gates are also common now.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Early latches were known variously as trigger circuits or multivibrators.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] They differ slightly from some of the definitions given below.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Lindley explains that he heard the story of the JK flip-flop from Eldred Nelson, who is responsible for coining the term while working at Hughes Aircraft.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops in use at Hughes at the time were all of the type that came to be known as J-K.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In designing a logical system, Nelson assigned letters to flip-flop inputs as follows: #1: A & B, #2: C & D, #3: E & F, #4: G & H, #5: J & K.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Nelson used the notations *j-input* and *k-input* in a patent application filed in 1953.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Transparent or asynchronous latches can be built around a single pair of cross-coupled inverting elements: vacuum tubes, bipolar transistors, field-effect transistors, inverters, and inverting logic gates have all been used in practical circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Clocked flip-flops are specially designed for synchronous systems; such devices ignore their inputs except at the transition of a dedicated clock signal (known as clocking, pulsing, or strobing).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Clocking causes the flip-flop either to change or to retain its output signal based upon the values of the input signals at the transition.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Some flip-flops change output on the rising edge of the clock, others on the falling edge.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Since the elementary amplifying stages are inverting, two stages can be connected in succession (as a cascade) to form the needed non-inverting amplifier.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In this configuration, each amplifier may be considered as an active inverting feedback network for the other inverting amplifier.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Thus the two stages are connected in a non-inverting loop although the circuit diagram is usually drawn as a symmetric cross-coupled pair (both the drawings are initially introduced in the Eccles–Jordan patent).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches can be divided into common types: SR (set-reset), D (data), T (toggle), and JK (see History section above).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The behavior of a particular type can be described by the characteristic equation that derives the *next* output (*Q*next) in terms of the input signal(s) and/or the current output, Q .
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When using static gates as building blocks, the most fundamental latch is the asynchronous *set-reset (SR) latch*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Its two inputs S and R can set the internal state to 1 using the combination S=1 and R=0, and can reset the internal state to 0 using the combination S=0 and R=1.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The SR latch can be constructed from a pair of cross-coupled NOR or NAND logic gates.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The stored bit is present on the output marked Q.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It is convenient to think of NAND, NOR, AND and OR as controlled operations, where one input is chosen as the control input set and the other bit as the input to be processed depending on the state of the control.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Essentially, they can all be used as switches that either set a specific value or let an input value pass.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The SR NOR latch consists of two parallel NOR gates where the output of each NOR is also fanned out into one input of the other NOR, as shown in the figure.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] We call these output-to-input connections *feedback inputs*, or simply *feedbacks*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The remaining inputs we will use as *control* inputs as explained above.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Notice that at this point, because everything is symmetric, it does not matter to which inputs the outputs are connected.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] We now break the symmetry by choosing which of the remaining control inputs will be our set and reset and we can call *set NOR* the NOR gate with the set control and *reset NOR* the NOR with the reset control; in the figures the set NOR is the bottom one and the reset NOR is the top one.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The output of the reset NOR will be our stored bit Q, while we will see that the output of the set NOR stores its complement Q.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] To derive the behavior of the SR NOR latch, consider S and R as control inputs and remember that, from the equations above, set and reset NOR with control 1 will fix their outputs to 0, while set and reset NOR with control 0 will act as a NOT gate.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The R = S = 1 combination is called a **restricted combination** or a **forbidden state** because, as both NOR gates then output zeros, it breaks the logical equation Q = **not** Q.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The combination is also inappropriate in circuits where *both* inputs may go low *simultaneously* (i.e. a transition from *restricted* to *hold*).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The output could remain in a metastable state and may eventually lock at either 1 or 0 depending on the propagation time relations between the gates (a race condition).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] To overcome the restricted combination, one can add gates to the inputs that would convert `(S, R) = (1, 1)` to one of the non-restricted combinations.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This is done in nearly every programmable logic controller.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, the restricted combination can be made to *toggle* the output.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit shown below is a basic NAND latch.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The inputs are also generally designated S and R for Set and Reset respectively.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Because the NAND inputs must normally be logic 1 to avoid affecting the latching action, the inputs are considered to be inverted in this circuit (or active low).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit uses the same feedback as SR NOR, just replacing NOR gates with NAND gates, to *remember* and retain its logical state even after the controlling input signals have changed.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Again, recall that a 1-controlled NAND always outputs 0, while a 0-controlled NAND acts as a NOT gate.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When the S and R inputs are both high, feedback maintains the Q outputs to the previous state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When either is zero, they fix their output bits to 0 while to other adapts to the complement.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] From a teaching point of view, SR latches drawn as a pair of cross-coupled components (transistors, gates, tubes, etc.) are often hard to understand for beginners.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] A didactically easier explanation is to draw the latch as a single feedback loop instead of the cross-coupling.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The following is an SR latch built with an AND gate with one inverted input and an OR gate.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Note that the inverter is not needed for the latch functionality, but rather to make both inputs high-active.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Note that the SR AND-OR latch has the benefit that S = 1, R = 1 is well defined.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In above version of the SR AND-OR latch it gives priority to the R signal over the S signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] If priority of S over R is needed, this can be achieved by connecting output Q to the output of the OR gate instead of the output of the AND gate.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The SR AND-OR latch is easier to understand, because both gates can be explained in isolation, again with the control view of AND and OR from above.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When neither S or R is set, then both the OR gate and the AND gate are in "hold mode", i.e., they let the input through, their output is the input from the feedback loop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When input S = 1, then the OR gate outputs 1, regardless of the other input from the feedback loop ("set mode").
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When input R = 1 then the AND gate outputs 0, regardless of the other input from the feedback loop ("reset mode").
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] And since the AND gate takes the output of the OR gate as input, R has priority over S.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Latches drawn as cross-coupled gates may look less intuitive, as the behavior of one gate appears to be intertwined with the other gate.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The standard NOR or NAND latches could also be re-drawn with the feedback loop, but in their case the feedback loop does not show the same signal value throughout the whole feedback loop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] However, the SR AND-OR latch has the drawback that it would need an extra inverter, if an inverted Q output is needed.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The JK latch is much less frequently used than the JK flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Hence, the JK latch is an SR latch that is made to *toggle* its output (oscillate between 0 and 1) when passed the input combination of 11.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Unlike the JK flip-flop, the 11 input combination for the JK latch is not very useful because there is no clock that directs toggling.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Latches are designed to be *transparent.* That is, input signal changes cause immediate changes in output.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Additional logic can be added to a transparent latch to make it *non-transparent* or *opaque* when another input (an *enable* input) is not asserted.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] A periodic *enable* input signal may be called a *write strobe*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When the *enable* input is a clock signal, the latch is said to be **level-sensitive** (to the level of the clock signal), as opposed to **edge-sensitive** like flip-flops below.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When several *transparent* latches follow each other, if they are all transparent at the same time, signals will propagate through them all.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] However, following a *transparent-high* latch by a *transparent-low* latch (or vice-versa) causes the state and output to only change on clock edges, forming what is called a *master–slave flip-flop*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] A *gated SR latch* can be made by adding a second level of NAND gates to an *inverted SR latch*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The extra NAND gates further invert the inputs so a *SR latch* becomes a *gated SR latch* (a *SR latch* would transform into a *gated SR latch* with inverted enable).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, a *gated SR latch* (with non-inverting enable) can be made by adding a second level of AND gates to a *SR latch*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] With E high (*enable* true), the signals can pass through the input gates to the encapsulated latch; all signal combinations except for (0, 0) = *hold* then immediately reproduce on the (Q, Q) output, i.e. the latch is *transparent*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] With E low (*enable* false) the latch is *closed (opaque)* and remains in the state it was left the last time E was high.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This latch exploits the fact that, in the two active input combinations (01 and 10) of a gated SR latch, R is the complement of S.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The input NAND stage converts the two D input states (0 and 1) to these two input combinations for the next SR latch by inverting the data input signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The low state of the *enable* signal produces the inactive *11* combination.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Thus a gated D-latch may be considered as a *one-input synchronous SR latch*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This configuration prevents application of the restricted input combination.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It is also known as *transparent latch*, *data latch*, or simply *gated latch*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It has a *data* input and an *enable* signal (sometimes named *clock*, or *control*).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The word *transparent* comes from the fact that, when the enable input is on, the signal propagates directly through the circuit, from the input D to the output Q.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Gated D-latches are also **level-sensitive** with respect to the level of the clock or enable signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Transparent latches are typically used as I/O ports or in asynchronous systems, or in synchronous two-phase systems (synchronous systems that use a two-phase clock), where two latches operating on different clock phases prevent data transparency as in a master–slave flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The truth table below shows that when the *e*nable input is 0, the D input has no effect on the output.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The classic gated latch designs have some undesirable characteristics.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] They require dual-rail logic or an inverter.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The input-to-output propagation may take up to three gate delays.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The input-to-output propagation is not constant – some outputs take two gate delays while others take three.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] A successful alternative is the Earle latch.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It requires only a single data input, and its output takes a constant two gate delays.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In addition, the two gate levels of the Earle latch can, in some cases, be merged with the last two gate levels of the circuits driving the latch because many common computational circuits have an OR layer followed by an AND layer as their last two levels.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Merging the latch function can implement the latch with no additional gate delays.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The merge is commonly exploited in the design of pipelined computers, and, in fact, was originally developed by John G.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Earle to be used in the IBM System/360 Model 91 for that purpose.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] If the middle NAND gate is omitted, then one gets the **polarity hold latch**, which is commonly used because it demands less logic.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] However, it is susceptible to logic hazard.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Intentionally skewing the clock signal can avoid the hazard.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop is widely used, and known as a *data* flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop captures the value of the D-input at a definite portion of the clock cycle (such as the rising edge of the clock).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] That captured value becomes the Q output.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] At other times, the output Q does not change.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop can be viewed as a memory cell, a zero-order hold, or a delay line.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Most D-type flip-flops in ICs have the capability to be forced to the set or reset state (which ignores the D and clock inputs).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Usually, the S = R = 1 condition (illegal in SR latches) is resolved in D-type flip-flops.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Setting S = R = 0 makes the flip-flop behave as described above.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] These flip-flops are very useful, as they form the basis for shift registers, which are an essential part of many electronic devices.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The advantage of the D flip-flop over the D-type *transparent latch* is that the signal on the D input pin is captured the moment the flip-flop is clocked, and subsequent changes on the D input will be ignored until the next clock event.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] An exception is that some flip-flops have a *reset* signal input, which will reset Q (to zero), and may be either asynchronous or synchronous with the clock.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The above circuit shifts the contents of the register to the right, one bit position on each active transition of the clock.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The input X is shifted into the leftmost bit position.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This circuit consists of two stages implemented by SR NAND latches.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The input stage (the two latches on the left) processes the clock and data signals to ensure correct input signals for the output stage (the single latch on the right).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] If the clock is low, both the output signals of the input stage are high regardless of the data input; the output latch is unaffected and it stores the previous state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When the clock signal changes from low to high, only one of the output voltages (depending on the data signal) goes low and sets/resets the output latch: if D = 0, the lower output becomes low; if D = 1, the upper output becomes low.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] As long as the clock signal stays high, these input-stage outputs keep their states regardless of the data input and force the output latch to stay in the corresponding state, as the input logical zero (of the output stage) remains active while the clock is high.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Any change of the data input while the clock is high will not change the states of the two input-stage latches.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Hence the role of the output latch is to store the data only while the clock is low.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit is closely related to the gated D latch as both the circuits convert the two D input states (0 and 1) to two input combinations (01 and 10) for the output SR latch by inverting the data input signal (both the circuits split the single D signal in two complementary S and R signals).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The difference is that NAND logical gates are used in the gated D latch, while SR NAND latches are used in the positive-edge-triggered D flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The role of these latches is to *lock* the active output producing low voltage (a logical zero); thus the positive-edge-triggered D flip-flop can also be thought of as a gated D latch with latched input gates.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] A master–slave D flip-flop is created by connecting two gated D latches in series, and inverting the *enable* input to one of them.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] For a positive-edge triggered master–slave D flip-flop, when the clock signal is low (logical 0) the *enable* seen by the first or *master* D latch (the inverted clock signal) is high (logical 1).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This allows the *master* latch to store the input value when the clock signal transitions from low to high.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] As the clock signal goes high (0 to 1) the inverted *enable* of the first latch goes low (1 to 0) and the value seen at the input to the master latch is *locked*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Nearly simultaneously, the twice inverted *enable* of the second or *slave* D latch transitions from low to high (0 to 1) with the clock signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This allows the signal captured at the rising edge of the clock by the now *locked* master latch to pass through the *slave* latch.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When the clock signal returns to low (1 to 0), the output of the *slave* latch is *locked*, and the value seen at the last rising edge of the clock is held while the *master* latch begins to accept new values in preparation for the next rising clock edge.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Removing the leftmost inverter in the circuit creates a D-type flip-flop that captures the D input on the *falling edge* of the clock signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-Flops that read in a new value on the rising and the falling edge of the clock are called dual-edge-triggered flip-flops.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Such a flip-flop may be built using two single-edge-triggered D-type flip-flops and a multiplexer, or by using two single-edge triggered D-type flip-flops and three XOR gates.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] An efficient functional alternative to a D flip-flop can be made with dynamic circuits (where information is stored in a capacitance) as long as it is clocked often enough; while not a true flip-flop, it is still called a flip-flop for its functional role.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] While the master–slave D element is triggered on the edge of a clock, its components are each triggered by clock levels.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The *edge-triggered D flip-flop*, as it is called even though it is not a true flip-flop, does not have the master–slave properties.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Edge-triggered D flip-flops are often implemented in integrated high-speed operations using dynamic logic.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This means that the digital output is stored on parasitic device capacitance while the device is not transitioning.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This design facilitates resetting by simply discharging one or more internal nodes.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] A common dynamic flip-flop variety is the true single-phase clock (TSPC) type which performs the flip-flop operation with little power and at high speeds.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] However, dynamic flip-flops will typically not work at static or low clock speeds: given enough time, leakage paths may discharge the parasitic capacitance enough to cause the flip-flop to enter invalid states.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] If the T input is high, the T flip-flop changes state ("toggles") on the triggering clock edge.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] If the T input is low, the flip-flop holds the previous value.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When T is held high, the toggle flip-flop divides the clock frequency by two; that is, if clock frequency is 4 MHz, the output frequency obtained from the flip-flop will be 2 MHz.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This "divide by" feature has application in various types of digital counters.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] A T flip-flop can also be built using a JK flip-flop (J & K pins are connected together and act as T) or a D flip-flop (T input XOR Qprevious drives the D input).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The JK flip-flop behaves like an edge-triggered SR flip-flop (J: Set, K: Reset) that replaces the illegal S = R = 1 condition with a *flip* or toggle command.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Setting J = K = 0 maintains the current state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The JK flip-flop is considered a universal flip-flop, because it can be configured to work as an SR flip-flop, a D flip-flop, or a T flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] For instance, to synthesize a D flip-flop, simply set K equal to the complement of J (input J will act as input D).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Similarly, to synthesize a T flip-flop, set K equal to J.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The input must be held steady in a period around the rising edge of the clock known as the aperture.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Imagine taking a picture of a frog on a lily pad.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Suppose the frog then jumps into the water.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] If you take a picture of the frog as it jumps into the water, you will get a blurry picture of the frog jumping into the water—it's not clear which state the frog was in.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] But if you take a picture while the frog sits steadily on the pad (or is steadily in the water), you will get a clear picture.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In the same way, the input to a flip-flop must be held steady during the *aperture* of the flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Short impulses applied to asynchronous inputs (set, reset) should not be applied completely within the recovery-removal period, or else it becomes entirely indeterminable whether the flip-flop will transition to the appropriate state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In another case, where an asynchronous signal simply makes one transition that happens to fall between the recovery/removal time, eventually the flip-flop will transition to the appropriate state, but a very short glitch may or may not appear on the output, dependent on the synchronous input signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This second situation may or may not have significance to a circuit design.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Set and Reset (and other) signals may be either synchronous or asynchronous and therefore may be characterized with either Setup/Hold or Recovery/Removal times, and synchronicity is very dependent on the design of the flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Differentiation between Setup/Hold and Recovery/Removal times is often necessary when verifying the timing of larger circuits because asynchronous signals may be found to be less critical than synchronous signals.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The differentiation offers circuit designers the ability to define the verification conditions for these types of signals independently.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops are subject to a problem called metastability, which can happen when two inputs, such as data and clock or clock and reset, are changing at about the same time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When the order is not clear, within appropriate timing constraints, the result is that the output may behave unpredictably, taking many times longer than normal to settle to one state or the other, or even oscillating several times before settling.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Theoretically, the time to settle down is not bounded.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The metastability in flip-flops can be avoided by ensuring that the data and control inputs are held valid and constant for specified periods before and after the clock pulse, called the **setup time** (tsu) and the **hold time** (th) respectively.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] These times are specified in the data sheet for the device, and are typically between a few nanoseconds and a few hundred picoseconds for modern devices.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Depending upon the flip-flop's internal organization, it is possible to build a device with a zero (or even negative) setup or hold time requirement but not both simultaneously.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Unfortunately, it is not always possible to meet the setup and hold criteria, because the flip-flop may be connected to a real-time signal that could change at any time, outside the control of the designer.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In this case, the best the designer can do is to reduce the probability of error to a certain level, depending on the required reliability of the circuit.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] One technique for suppressing metastability is to connect two or more flip-flops in a chain, so that the output of each one feeds the data input of the next, and all devices share a common clock.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] With this method, the probability of a metastable event can be reduced to a negligible value, but never to zero.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The probability of metastability gets closer and closer to zero as the number of flip-flops connected in series is increased.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The number of flip-flops being cascaded is referred to as the *ranking*; *dual-ranked* flip flops (two flip-flops in series) is a common situation.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] So-called metastable-hardened flip-flops are available, which work by reducing the setup and hold times as much as possible, but even these cannot eliminate the problem entirely.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This is because metastability is more than simply a matter of circuit design.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] When the transitions in the clock and the data are close together in time, the flip-flop is forced to decide which event happened first.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] However fast the device is made, there is always the possibility that the input events will be so close together that it cannot detect which one happened first.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] It is therefore logically impossible to build a perfectly metastable-proof flip-flop.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops are sometimes characterized for a maximum settling time (the maximum time they will remain metastable under specified conditions).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In this case, dual-ranked flip-flops that are clocked slower than the maximum allowed metastability time will provide proper conditioning for asynchronous (e.g., external) signals.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Another important timing value for a flip-flop is the clock-to-output delay (common symbol in data sheets: tCO) or propagation delay (tP), which is the time a flip-flop takes to change its output after the clock edge.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The time for a high-to-low transition (tPHL) is sometimes different from the time for a low-to-high transition (tPLH).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This relationship between tCO and th is normally guaranteed if the flip-flops are physically identical.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Furthermore, for correct operation, it is easy to verify that the clock period has to be greater than the sum tsu + th.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops can be generalized in at least two ways: by making them 1-of-N instead of 1-of-2, and by adapting them to logic with more than two states.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In the special cases of 1-of-3 encoding, or multi-valued ternary logic, such an element may be referred to as a *flip-flap-flop*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In a conventional flip-flop, exactly one of the two complementary outputs is high.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] This can be generalized to a memory element with N outputs, exactly one of which is high (alternatively, where exactly one of N is low).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The output is therefore always a one-hot (respectively *one-cold*) representation.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] The construction is similar to a conventional cross-coupled flip-flop; each output, when high, inhibits all the other outputs.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, more or less conventional flip-flops can be used, one per output, with additional circuitry to make sure only one at a time can be true.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] Another generalization of the conventional flip-flop is a memory element for multi-valued logic.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In this case the memory element retains exactly one of the logic states until the control inputs induce a change.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/flip-flop-electronics] In addition, a multiple-valued clock can also be used, leading to new possible clock transitions.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Metastable states are inherent features of asynchronous digital systems, and of systems with more than one independent clock domain.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] In self-timed asynchronous systems, arbiters are designed to allow the system to proceed only after the metastability has resolved, so the metastability is a normal condition, not an error condition.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] In synchronous systems with asynchronous inputs, synchronizers are designed to make the probability of a synchronization failure acceptably small.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Metastable states are avoidable in fully synchronous systems when the input setup and hold time requirements on flip-flops are satisfied.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] A simple example of metastability can be found in an SR NOR latch, when *both* Set and Reset inputs are true (R=1 and S=1) and then both transition to false (R=0 and S=0) at about the same time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Both outputs Q and Q are initially held at 0 by the simultaneous Set and Reset inputs.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] After both Set and Reset inputs change to false, the flip-flop will (eventually) end up in one of two stable states, one of Q and Q true and the other false.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] The final state will depend on which of R or S returns to zero first, chronologically, but if both transition at about the same time, the resulting metastability, with intermediate or oscillatory output levels, can take arbitrarily long to resolve to a stable state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] In electronics, an *arbiter* is a circuit designed to determine which of several signals arrive first.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Arbiters are used in asynchronous circuits to order computational activities for shared resources to prevent concurrent incorrect operations.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Arbiters are used on the inputs of fully synchronous systems, and also between clock domains, as synchronizers for input signals.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Although they can minimize the occurrence of metastability to very low probabilities, all arbiters nevertheless have metastable states, which are unavoidable at the boundaries of regions of the input state space resulting in different outputs.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Synchronous circuit design techniques make digital circuits that are resistant to the failure modes that can be caused by metastability.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] A **clock domain** is defined as a group of flip-flops with a common clock.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Such architectures can form a circuit guaranteed free of metastability (below a certain maximum clock frequency, above which first metastability, then outright failure occur), assuming a low-skew common clock.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] However, even then, if the system has a dependence on any continuous inputs then these are likely to be vulnerable to metastable states.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Synchronizer circuits are used to reduce the likelihood of metastability when receiving an asynchronous input or when transferring signals between different clock domains.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Synchronizers may take the form of a cascade of D flip-flops (e.g. the shift register in Figure 3).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Although each flip-flop stage adds an additional clock cycle of latency to the input data stream, each stage provides an opportunity to resolve metastability.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Such synchronizers can be engineered to reduce metastability to a tolerable rate.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Schmitt triggers can also be used to reduce the likelihood of metastability, but as the researcher Chaney demonstrated in 1979, even Schmitt triggers may become metastable.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Although metastability is well understood and architectural techniques to control it are known, it persists as a failure mode in equipment.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Serious computer and digital hardware bugs caused by metastability have a fascinating social history.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Many engineers have refused to believe that a bistable device can enter into a state that is neither *true* nor *false* and has a positive probability that it will remain indefinite for any given period of time, albeit with exponentially decreasing probability over time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] However, metastability is an inevitable result of any attempt to map a continuous domain to a discrete one.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] At the boundaries in the continuous domain between regions which map to different discrete outputs, points arbitrarily close together in the continuous domain map to different outputs, making a decision as to which output to select a difficult and potentially lengthy process.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] If the inputs to an arbiter or flip-flop arrive almost simultaneously, the circuit most likely will traverse a point of metastability.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Metastability remains poorly understood in some circles, and various engineers have proposed their own circuits said to solve or filter out the metastability; typically these circuits simply shift the occurrence of metastability from one place to another.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Chips using multiple clock sources are often tested with tester clocks that have fixed phase relationships, not the independent clocks drifting past each other that will be experienced during operation.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] This usually explicitly prevents the metastable failure mode that will occur in the field from being seen or reported.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/metastability-electronics] Proper testing for metastability frequently employs clocks of slightly different frequencies and ensuring correct circuit operation.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A **race condition** or **race hazard** is the condition of an electronics, software, or other system where the system's substantive behavior is dependent on the sequence or timing of uncontrollable events, leading to unexpected or inconsistent results.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] It becomes a bug when one or more of the possible behaviors is undesirable.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The term *race condition* was in use by 1954, for example in David A.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Huffman's doctoral thesis "The synthesis of sequential switching circuits".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Race conditions can occur especially in logic circuits or concurrent or distributed software programs.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Using mutual exclusion can prevent race conditions.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A typical example of a race condition may occur when a logic gate combines signals that have traveled along different paths from the same source.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The inputs to the gate can change at slightly different times in response to a change in the source signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The output may, for a brief period, change to an unwanted state before settling back to the designed state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Certain systems can tolerate such glitches, but if this output functions as a clock signal for further systems that contain memory, for example, the system can rapidly depart from its designed behaviour (in effect, the temporary glitch becomes a permanent glitch).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Consider, for example, a two-input AND gate fed with the following logic: ${\text{output}}=A\wedge {\overline {A}}$ A logic signal A on one input and its Boolean negation ${\bar {A}}$ on another input can never, in theory, output a true value as $A\wedge {\overline {A}}\neq 1$ .
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] If, however, changes in the value of A take longer to propagate to the second input than the first when A changes from false to true then a brief period will ensue during which both inputs are true, and so the gate's output will also be true.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A practical example of a race condition can occur when logic circuitry is used to detect certain outputs of a counter.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] If all the bits of the counter do not change exactly simultaneously, there will be intermediate patterns that can trigger false matches.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A *critical race condition* occurs when the order in which internal variables are changed determines the eventual state that the state machine will end up in.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A *non-critical race condition* occurs when the order in which internal variables are changed does not determine the eventual state that the state machine will end up in.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A *static race condition* occurs when a signal and its complement are combined.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A *dynamic race condition* occurs when it results in multiple transitions when only one is intended.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] They are due to interaction between gates.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] It can be eliminated by using no more than two levels of gating.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] An *essential race condition* occurs when an input has two transitions in less than the total feedback propagation time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Sometimes they are cured using inductive delay line elements to effectively increase the time duration of an input signal.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Design techniques such as Karnaugh maps encourage designers to recognize and eliminate race conditions before they cause problems.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] By simplifying Boolean expressions and analyzing the relationships between input variables, designers can reduce the likelihood of unintended signal changes that may lead to race conditions.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In many cases, logic redundancy can be intentionally added to digital circuits to eliminate certain types of races.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Although redundancy increases the number of logic gates, it can stabilize signal transitions and prevent temporary glitches that occur when signals change at slightly different times.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Engineers may also apply careful timing control and synchronization methods in sequential circuits.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] For example, using clocked elements such as flip-flops can help ensure that signals change in a predictable manner, reducing the risk of race conditions in complex digital systems.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Despite these precautions, some logic elements may still enter metastable states.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In such cases, a circuit temporarily remains in an unstable condition between logical states, which can propagate uncertain signals through the system and create additional challenges for circuit designers.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A race condition can arise in software when a computer program has multiple code paths that are executing at the same time.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] If the multiple code paths take a different amount of time than expected, they can finish in a different order than expected, which can cause software bugs due to unanticipated behavior.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A race can also occur between two programs, resulting in security issues.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Critical race conditions cause invalid execution and software bugs and often happen when processes or threads depend on some shared state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Operations upon shared states are done in critical sections that must be mutually exclusive.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Failure to obey this rule can corrupt the shared state.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A data race is a type of race condition.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Data races are important parts of various formal memory models.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The memory model defined in the C11 and C++11 standards specify that a C or C++ program containing a data race has undefined behavior.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A race condition can be difficult to reproduce and debug because the result is nondeterministic and depends on the relative timing between interfering threads.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Problems of this nature can therefore disappear when running in debug mode, adding extra logging, or attaching a debugger.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A bug that disappears like this during debugging attempts is often referred to as a *Heisenbug*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] It is therefore better to avoid race conditions by careful software design.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Assume that two threads each increment the value of a global integer variable by 1.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In the case shown above, the final value is 2, as expected.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] However, if the two threads run simultaneously without locking or synchronization (via semaphores), the outcome of the operation could be wrong.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In this case, the final value is 1 instead of the expected result of 2.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This occurs because here the increment operations are not mutually exclusive.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Mutually exclusive operations are those that cannot be interrupted while accessing some resource such as a memory location.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Not everyone regards data races as a subset of race conditions.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This implies that a data race is different from a race condition as it is possible to have nondeterminism due to timing even in a program without data races, for example, in a program in which all memory accesses use only atomic operations.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] On many platforms, special memory operations are provided for simultaneous access; in such cases, typically simultaneous access using these special operations is safe, but simultaneous access using other memory operations is dangerous.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Sometimes such special operations (which are safe for simultaneous access) are called *atomic* or *synchronization* operations, whereas the ordinary operations (which are unsafe for simultaneous access) are called *data* operations.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This is probably why the term is *data* race; on many platforms, where there is a race condition involving only *synchronization* operations, such a race may be nondeterministic but otherwise safe; but a *data* race could lead to memory corruption or undefined behavior.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The precise definition of data race differs across formal concurrency models.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This matters because concurrent behavior is often non-intuitive and so formal reasoning is sometimes applied.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The parts of this definition relating to signal handlers are idiosyncratic to C++ and are not typical of definitions of *data race*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Here we have two memory operations accessing the same location, one of which is a write.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] If neither "X happens-before Y" nor "Y happens-before X", then we say that X and Y are "not ordered by the hb1 relation".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] So, the clause "... and they are not ordered by the hb1 relation of the execution" can be intuitively translated as "... and X and Y are potentially concurrent".
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The paper considers dangerous only those situations in which at least one of the memory operations is a *data operation*; in other parts of this paper, the paper also defines a class of *synchronization operations* which are safe for potentially simultaneous use, in contrast to *data operations*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A critical difference between the C++ approach and the Java approach is that in C++, a data race is undefined behavior, whereas in Java, a data race merely affects *inter-thread actions*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] An important facet of data races is that in some contexts, a program that is free of data races is guaranteed to execute in a sequentially consistent manner, greatly easing reasoning about the concurrent behavior of the program.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Formal memory models that provide such a guarantee are said to exhibit an SC for DRF (*sequential consistency for data race freedom*) property.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This approach has been said to have achieved recent consensus (presumably compared to approaches that guarantee sequential consistency in all cases, or approaches which do not guarantee it at all).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In other words, in C++, some correct programs are not sequentially consistent.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This approach is thought to give C++ programmers the freedom to choose faster program execution at the cost of giving up ease of reasoning about their program.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] There are various theorems, often provided in the form of memory models, that provide SC for DRF guarantees given various contexts.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The DRF1 memory model provides SC for DRF and allows the optimizations of the WO (weak ordering), RCsc (release consistency with sequentially consistent special operations), VAX memory model, and data-race-free-0 memory models.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] The PLpc memory model provides SC for DRF and allows the optimizations of the TSO (total store order), PSO, PC (processor consistency), and RCpc (release consistency with processor consistency special operations) models.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] DRFrlx provides a sketch of an SC for DRF theorem in the presence of relaxed atomics.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Many software race conditions have associated computer security implications.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A race condition allows an attacker with access to a shared resource to cause other actors that utilize that resource to malfunction, resulting in effects including denial of service and privilege escalation.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A specific kind of race condition involves checking for a predicate (e.g. for authentication), then acting on the predicate, while the state can change between the *time-of-check* and the *time-of-use*.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] When this kind of bug exists in security-sensitive code, a security vulnerability called a time-of-check to time-of-use (*TOCTTOU*) bug is created.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Race conditions are also intentionally used to create hardware random number generators and physically unclonable functions.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] PUFs can be created by designing circuit topologies with identical paths to a node and relying on manufacturing variations to randomly determine which paths will complete first.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] By measuring each manufactured circuit's specific set of race condition outcomes, a profile can be collected for each circuit and kept secret in order to later verify a circuit's identity.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Two or more programs may collide in their attempts to modify or access a file system, which can result in data corruption or privilege escalation.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] File locking provides a commonly used solution.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A more cumbersome remedy involves organizing the system in such a way that one unique process (running a daemon or the like) has exclusive access to the file, and all other processes that need to access the data in that file do so only via interprocess communication with that one process.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This requires synchronization at the process level.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A different form of race condition exists in file systems where unrelated programs may affect each other by suddenly using up available resources such as disk space, memory space, or processor cycles.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Software not carefully designed to anticipate and handle this race situation may then become unpredictable.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Such a risk may be overlooked for a long time in a system that seems very reliable.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] But eventually enough data may accumulate or enough other software may be added to critically destabilize many parts of a system.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] An example of this occurred with the near loss of the Mars Rover "Spirit" not long after landing, which occurred due to deleted file entries causing the file system library to consume all available memory space.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A solution is for software to request and reserve all the resources it will need before beginning a task; if this request fails then the task is postponed, avoiding the many points where failure could have occurred.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Alternatively, each of those points can be equipped with error handling, or the success of the entire task can be verified afterwards, before continuing.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A more common approach is to simply verify that enough system resources are available before starting a task; however, this may not be adequate because in complex systems the actions of other running programs can be unpredictable.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In networking, consider a distributed chat network like IRC, where a user who starts a channel automatically acquires channel-operator privileges.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] However, the latency across the network makes possible the kind of race condition described.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In this case, heading off race conditions by imposing a form of control over access to the shared resource—say, appointing one server to control who holds what privileges—would mean turning the distributed network into a centralized one (at least for that one part of the network operation).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Race conditions can also exist when a computer program is written with non-blocking sockets, in which case the performance of the program can be dependent on the speed of the network link.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Software flaws in life-critical systems can be disastrous.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Race conditions were among the flaws in the Therac-25 radiation therapy machine, which led to the death of at least three patients and injuries to several more.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Another example is the energy management system provided by GE Energy and used by Ohio-based FirstEnergy Corp (among other power facilities).
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] A race condition existed in the alarm subsystem; when three sagging power lines were tripped simultaneously, the condition prevented alerts from being raised to the monitoring technicians, delaying their awareness of the problem.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] This software flaw eventually led to the North American Blackout of 2003.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] GE Energy later developed a software patch to correct the previously undiscovered error.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Many software tools exist to help detect race conditions in software.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] They can be largely categorized into two groups: static analysis tools and dynamic analysis tools.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Thread Safety Analysis is a static analysis tool for annotation-based intra-procedural static analysis, originally implemented as a branch of gcc, and now reimplemented in Clang, supporting PThreads.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Race conditions are a common concern in human-computer interaction design and software usability.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In UK railway signalling, a race condition would arise in the carrying out of Rule 55.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] According to this rule, if a train was stopped on a running line by a signal, the locomotive fireman would walk to the signal box in order to remind the signalman that the train was present.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] In at least one case, at Winwick in 1934, an accident occurred because the signalman accepted another train before the fireman arrived.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Modern signalling practice removes the race condition by making it possible for the driver to instantaneously contact the signal box by radio.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Race conditions are not confined to digital systems.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] Neuroscience is demonstrating that race conditions can occur in mammal brains as well.
[src:clock-domain-crossing/race-condition] One demonstrated race is between neural pathways that execute planned movement and separate pathways that can cancel said movement.
